title: For Sale:  Vintage Military M3 Infrared Night Vision Scope 1943-1968
postcontent: For sale is a RARE Infrared Night Vision Scope, manufactured by American Optical on August 31, 1950. This infrared Scope was first manufactured in 1943 for use in the Pacific against the Japanese forces and was used in Korea and Vietnam until 1968. The case is in perfect condition as well as the scope. I cannot say that it works because I have not powered it up. The Battery has never had any acid in it. The set is missing the transformer that converts 6 volts from the battery to 20,000 to power the optical tube. The set is also missing the power cable that connects the transformer to the Infrared Scope. The scope has all the correct cables. The Lens is in perfect condition without any cracks or imperfections. The set is also missing the tool pouch which is very hard to find and some miscellaneous small spare parts. There are extra parts. There is a spare battery that has been converted to a 6 volt solid state battery. There is a new trigger assembly that is still in its original box and the upper hand guard required to mount the infrared scope on a M1/M2 carbine. There are also two extra elevation cams that are very hard to find. There is also an original TM5-9342 manual, that is also hard to find. I have not seen a Vintage Infrared Scope offered in this great condition before.

title: For Sale:  Rare 1935 Mosin Hex Izhevsk
postcontent: If you are a collector or investor you know what this is. 1935 was a low production year for Izhevsk and also the year they switched from hex to round receivers. Very few rifle were made in early 1935 with hex receivers and the rarity factor is 5 for this rifle. I believe it is much more rare than others with the same rating. I have only seen 2 of these offered for sale in the last 5 years. These are much more rarer than the MO double dates and pre 1928 ex dragoons. I don't think you will see one again for a long time. Numbers matching and not counter bored.

title: For Sale:  6.5mm Beretta I-rifle
postcontent: This is a 6.5mm sporterized Japanese "Type I" (capital I, not the number one) rifle, meaning it was made in Italy for the Imperial Japanese Navy in World War II. The gun has an Italian M1891 action, modified to take a Mauser (Arisaka design) magazine chambered for the 6.5mmx50SR (SemiRimfire) Japanese cartridge. About 60,000 of these Italian rifles were ordered by Japan's navy in 1937 when all of Japan's Type 38 Arisaka rifles were reserved for the army. More than 60,000 Italian rifles were delivered but many were warehoused unused or were lost on IJN ships. Those captured or surrendered at the end of WW II were in very good condition. Produced primarily by Beretta, the rifle was designated by the Italians as the "Beretta Fucile Tipo I per L'esportazione," which, roughly translated means "Beretta Rifle Type I for Export." The serial number of this particular gun is F7821, the F prefix identifying it as having been made by Beretta at Italy's Gardone Arsenal. Students of both Italian and Japanese World War II rifles have found much to admire in the Type I, noting that the chambers were cut to much closer tolerances, making the gun more accurate than the Japanese-made Arisaka. Another plus, the action is a full inch shorter and lighter than the Japanese adaptation of the Mauser design, with a fit and finish conforming to the highest standards of pre-war Beretta workmanship. This rifle does not have its original military stock but a sporterised one of quality wood with a recoil pad. It makes for a fine hunting rifle on deer-sized game. The gun comes with a complete set of RCBS reloading dies, including shell holder, and four boxes of ammo, two with 139gr Norma boattails and two with 140gr Hornady SP. Bullet weights for the 6.5mm (.264 inches) range from 120gr SP to Norma's 156gr round nose "Alaska." But most reloaders believe 156gr is too heavy for the 6.5mm round, favoring weights between 129-140 grains.
